earch/ViewClinicalTrials.aspx?cdrid=298862&protocolsearchid=1878935&version=healthprofessional NCCTG-N9943] || Phase I/II Study of Gemcitabine and Pemetrexed Disodium in Patients With Unresectable or Metastatic Biliary Tract or Gallbladder Cancer |}

A lot of experiments just have two possible outcomes, generally referred to as "success" and "failure". If such an experiment is independently repeated we call them (a series of) '''Bernoulli trials'''. Usually the probability of success is called p. The repetition may be done in several ways:

*a fixed number of times (n); as a consequence the observed number of successes is stochastic;
*until a fixed number of successes (m) is observed; as a consequence the number of experiments is stochastic;

In the first case the number of successes is Binomial distributed with parameters n and p. For n=1 the distribution is also called the Bernoulli distribution.
In the second case the number of experiments is Negative Binomial distributed with parameters m and p. For m=1 the distribution is also called the Geometric distribution.

{{AltBookCat}}

{{Calculus/Top Nav|Volume of solids of revolution|Surface area}}
Suppose that we are given a function <math>f</math> that is continuous on an interval {{nowrap begin}}<math>[a,b]</math>{{nowrap end}} and we want to calculate the length of the curve drawn out by the graph of <math>f(x)</math> from {{nowrap begin}}<math>x=a</math>{{nowrap end}} to {{nowrap begin}}<math>x=b</math>{{nowrap end}}. If the graph were a straight line this would be easy — the formula for the length of the line is given by Pythagoras' theorem. And if the graph were a piecewise linear function we can calculate the length by adding up the length of each piece.
The problem is that most graphs are not linear. Nevertheless we can estimate the length of the curve by approximating it with straight lines. Suppose the curve <math>C</math> is given by the formula {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=f(x)</math>{{nowrap end}} for {{nowrap begin}}<math>a\le x\le b</math>{{nowrap end}}. We divide the interval {{nowrap begin}}<math>[a,b]</math>{{nowrap end}} into <math>n</math> subintervals with equal width <math>\Delta x</math> and endpoints {{nowrap begin}}<math>x_0,x_1,\ldots,x_n</math>{{nowrap end}}. Now let {{nowrap begin}}<math>y_i=f(x_i)</math>{{nowrap end}} so {{nowrap begin}}<math>P_i=(x_i,y_i)</math>{{nowrap end}} is the point on the curve above <math>x_i</math>. The length of the straight line between <math>P_i</math> and <math>P_{i+1}</math> is :<math> |P_iP_{i+1}| = \sqrt{ (y_{i+1} - y_{i})^2 + (x_{i+1}-{x_i})^2}</math>
So an estimate of the length of the curve <math>C</math> is the sum :<math> \sum_{i=0}^{n-1} |P_iP_{i+1}| </math>
As we divide the interval <math>[a,b]</math> into more pieces this gives a better estimate for the length of <math>C</math>. In fact we make that a definition.
{{Calculus/Def | title=Length of a Curve | text=The length of the curve <math>y=f(x)</math> for <math>a\le x\le b</math> is defined to be :<math>L = \lim_{n\to \infty} \sum_{i=0}^{n-1} |P_{i+1}P_i|</math> }}
== The Arclength Formula ==
Suppose that <math>f'</math> is continuous on {{nowrap begin}}<math>[a,b]</math>{{nowrap end}}. Then the length of the curve given by {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=f(x)</math>{{nowrap end}} between <math>a</math> and <math>b</math> is given by :<math> L = \int_a^b \sqrt{ 1+ (f'(x))^2 } dx</math> And in Leibniz notation :<math> L = \int_a^b \sqrt{ 1+ \left(\frac{dy}{dx}\right)^2 } dx</math>
'''Proof:''' Consider {{nowrap begin}}<math>y_{i+1} - y_i= f(x_{i+1}) -f(x_i).</math>{{nowrap end}} By the [[Calculus/Mean Value Theorem for Functions|Mean Value Theorem]] there is a point <math> z_i</math> in {{nowrap begin}}<math>(x_{i+1},x_i)</math>{{nowrap end}} such that :<math> y_{i+1} - y_i= f(x_{i+1}) -f(x_i)= f'(z_i) (x_{i+1}-x_i)\,</math>
So :<math>\begin{align}|P_iP_{i+1}|&=\sqrt{ (y_{i+1} - y_{i})^2 + (x_{i+1}-x_i)^2}\\ &=\sqrt{ (f'(z_i))^2 (x_{i+1}-x_i)^2 + (x_{i+1}-x_i)^2 }\\ &=\sqrt{ (1+(f'(z_i))^2) (x_{i+1}-x_i)^2 }\\ &=\sqrt{ (1+(f'(z_i))^2)} \Delta x\end{align}</math>
Putting this into the definition of the length of <math>C</math> gives
:<math>L=\lim_{n\to \infty} \sum_{i=0}^{n-1} \sqrt{ (1+(f'(z_i))^2)} \Delta x</math>
Now this is the definition of the integral of the function {{nowrap begin}}<math>g(x) = \sqrt{1+(f'(x))^2}</math>{{nowrap end}} between <math>a</math> and <math>b</math> (notice that <math>g</math> is continuous because we are assuming that <math>f'</math> is continuous). Hence
:<math>L=\int_a^b \sqrt{1+(f'(x))^2} dx</math>
as claimed.
{{ExampleRobox|title=Example: Length of the curve {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=2x</math>{{nowrap end}} from {{nowrap begin}}<math>x=0</math>{{nowrap end}} to {{nowrap begin}}<math>x=1</math>{{nowrap end}}}} As a sanity check of our formula, let's calculate the length of the "curve" {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=2x</math>{{nowrap end}} from {{nowrap begin}}<math>x=0</math>{{nowrap end}} to {{nowrap begin}}<math>x=1</math>{{nowrap end}}. First let's find the answer using the Pythagorean Theorem. :<math>P_0=(0,0)</math> and :<math>P_1=(1,2)</math> so the length of the curve, <math>s</math>, is :<math>s=\sqrt{2^2+1^2}=\sqrt{5}</math> Now let's use the formula :<math>s=\int_0^1 \sqrt{1+\left(\frac{d(2x)}{dx}\right)^2}=\int_0^1 \sqrt{1+2^2}=\sqrt{5}x\bigr|_0^1=\sqrt{5}</math> {{Robox/Close}}
===Exercises=== {{question-answer|question=1. Find the length of the curve {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=x^{3/2}</math>{{nowrap end}} from {{nowrap begin}}<math>x=0</math>{{nowrap end}} to {{nowrap begin}}<math>x=1</math>{{nowrap end}}.|answer={{noprint| :<math>\frac{13^{3/2}-8}{27}</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=2. Find the length of the curve {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=\frac{e^x+e^{-x}}{2}</math>{{nowrap end}} from {{nowrap begin}}<math>x=0</math>{{nowrap end}} to {{nowrap begin}}<math>x=1</math>{{nowrap end}}.|answer={{noprint| :<math>\frac{e-\frac{1}{e}}{2}</math>}}}} {{noprint|[[Calculus/Arc_length/Solutions|Solutions]]}}
== Arclength of a parametric curve ==
For a parametric curve, that is, a curve defined by {{nowrap begin}}<math>x=f(t)</math>{{nowrap end}} and {{nowrap begin}}<math>y=g(t)</math>{{nowrap end}}, the formula is slightly different: :<math>L = \int_a^b \sqrt{ (f'(t))^2 + (g'(t))^2 }\,dt</math>
'''Proof:''' The proof is analogous to the previous one: Consider {{nowrap begin}}<math>y_{i+1} - y_i= g(t_{i+1}) -g(t_i)</math>{{nowrap end}} and {{nowrap begin}}<math>x_{i+1} - x_i= f(t_{i+1}) -f(t_i)</math>{{nowrap end}}. By the Mean Value Theorem there are points <math>c_i</math> and <math>d_i</math> in {{nowrap begin}}<math>(t_{i+1},t_i)</math>{{nowrap end}} such that :<math> y_{i+1} - y_i= g(t_{i+1}) -g(t_i)= g'(c_i) (t_{i+1}-t_i)\,</math> and :<math> x_{i+1} - x_i= f(t_{i+1}) -f(t_i)= f'(d_i) (t_{i+1}-t_i)\,</math>
So :<math>\begin{align}|P_iP_{i+1}|&=\sqrt{ (y_{i+1} - y_{i})^2 + (x_{i+1}-x_i)^2}\\ &=\sqrt{ (g'(c_i))^2 (t_{i+1}-t_i)^2 + (f'(d_i))^2 (t_{i+1}-t_i)^2 }\\ &=\sqrt{ (f'(d_i))^2)+(g'(c_i))^2) (t_{i+1}-t_i)^2 }\\ &=\sqrt{ (f'(d_i))^2 + (g'(c_i))^2} \Delta t\end{align}</math>
Putting this into the definition of the length of the curve gives :<math>L=\lim_{n\to \infty} \sum_{i=0}^{n-1} \sqrt{ (f'(d_i))^2 + (g'(c_i))^2 } \Delta t</math> This is equivalent to: :<math>L=\int_a^b \sqrt{ (f'(t))^2 + (g'(t))^2}\,dt</math>
===Exercises=== {{question-answer|question=3. Find the circumference of the circle given by the parametric equations {{nowrap begin}}<math>x(t)=R\cos(t)</math>{{nowrap end}}, {{nowrap begin}}<math>y(t)=R\sin(t)</math>{{nowrap end}}, with <math>t</math> running from <math>0</math> to <math>2\pi</math>.|answer={{noprint| :<math>2\pi R</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=4. Find the length of one arch of the [[w:Cycloid|<u>cycloid</u>]] given by the parametric equations {{nowrap begin}}<math>x(t)=R(t-\sin(t))</math>{{nowrap end}}, {{nowrap begin}}<math>y(t)=R(1-\cos(t))</math>{{nowrap end}}, with <math>t</math> running from <math>0</math> to <math>2\pi</math>.|answer={{noprint| :<math>8R</math>}}}} {{noprint|[[Calculus/Arc_length/Solutions|Solutions]]}}
